ealogy.org/sfbtrum.htm","page":"Truman & Hooker"},{"short":"San Francisco city directories"},{"short":"Pacific-Union Club Officers & Members 1905"},{"short":"Findagrave (veteran flag noted)"}],"careers":[{"role":"Receiving Teller","employer":"First National Bank of San Francisco","location":"San Francisco CA","start_year":1881,"end_year":1885,"notes":"Per period business biography: 'He was receiving teller in the First National Bank from 1881 till 1885' — entry-level banking position from age 21 to 25."},{"role":"Partner","employer":"Truman & Hooker (hay presses, agricultural implements, wagons, buggies)","location":"421 Market Street, San Francisco CA","start_year":1885,"end_year":1925,"notes":"Joined Irwin J. Truman's existing firm in 1885 at age 25, leaving his First National Bank position. The firm had been founded by Truman in 1867 at 1717 Front Street SF as a manufacturer and dealer in HAY PRESSES; in ~1882 (after 15 years) they added agricultural implements + wagons + buggies. Osgood had charge of the buying and selling departments. Wholesale + retail; trade extended over the Pacific Coast and to the Sandwich Islands [Hawaii], with goods also shipped to Russia and Egypt. ~30 employees. Per period business biography: 'Mr. Hooker is a quick, intelligent and obliging business man, a Californian of whom California has no reason to be ashamed.'"}],"education":[{"institution":"San Francisco public schools"},{"institution":"Phillips Exeter Academy","location":"Exeter, New Hampshire","notes":"New England prep school"},{"institution":"Phillips Exeter Academy","location":"Exeter NH","notes":"Per period business biography: 'educated in the public schools of this city [SF] and at Exeter, New Hampshire.' Phillips Exeter Academy is the prestigious New England preparatory school. The NH connection ties to his father's New Hampshire roots (Charles Gay Hooker b. Hinsdale NH 1820)."}],"memberships":[{"organization":"Pacific-Union Club","location":"San Francisco CA","year":1905,"notes":"Listed in 1905 Officers & Members directory; address 16 Drumm"},{"organization":"Bohemian Club","role":"Member","years":[1892],"location":"San Francisco CA","notes":"Per Bohemian Club Officers & Members 1892 roster: 'HOOKER, G. Osgood' — alongside brother Robert G. Hooker and brother-in-law George H. Lent."},{"organization":"Pacific-Union Club","role":"Member","years":[null],"location":"San Francisco CA","notes":"One of SF's most exclusive private clubs. Membership inferred from Sam's earlier note about Robert G. Hooker + Eugene Lent being members; Osgood likely also a member as the elder brother. Specific roster year not yet confirmed."}],"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"career","header":"Banker at twenty, importer at twenty-five","body":"From 1881 to 1885 he was receiving teller at the First National Gold Bank of San Francisco. Then he joined Irwin Truman to form Truman and Hooker, importers of agricultural machinery."},{"number":2,"category":"career","header":"Sold San Francisco wagons to Russia and Egypt","body":"Truman and Hooker's trade extended across the Pacific to Hawaii, then on to Russia and Egypt. The reach was unusual for an 1890s San Francisco firm."},{"number":3,"category":"education","header":"Phillips Exeter prepared him from California","body":"He left San Francisco public schools for the New Hampshire boarding school in his teens. Eighty years later Jay Rockefeller would follow the same path."},{"number":4,"category":"family","header":"His Bohemian Club fellow married his sister","body":"In 1892 he and his brother Robert appeared on the Bohemian Club roster alongside George H. Lent. That same year Lent married their sister Bessie Augusta Hooker — bringing the brother-in-law into the family."}],"cross_connections":[{"type":"civic_connection","related_id":"X02298","display_label":"Bohemian Club fellows the year Lent married his sister Bessie.","link_text":"George Heydenfeldt Lent"}],"military_service":[{"notes":"Per Findagrave: VVETERAN designation. Era and conflict unspecified — given his birth year 1860, he would have been ~38 at the Spanish-American War (1898) which is the most likely fit. Other possibilities: military service in California state militia. INVESTIGATION FLAG."}],"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST094"},{"institution_id":"INST099"},{"institution_id":"INST102"},{"institution_id":"INST103"}],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"slug":"charles-hooker-1860"},"H05205":{"id":"H05205","former_ids":[],"is_placeholder":false,"gender":"male","has_descendants_documented":false,"classification":{"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_thomas_spouse":false,"is_talcott_spouse":false,"generation_from_thomas":10,"is_easter_egg":false,"include_in_path_calculation":true,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true},"bio":{"first_name":"Osgood","last_name":"Hooker","married_names":[],"gender":"male","display_name":"Osgood Hooker","photo_url":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dc5clrqtw/image/upload/v1777258929/osgoodhooker_mtdftp.png","photo_notes":"Cloudinary; supplied by Sam"},"birth":{"year":1897,"month":8,"day":6,"city":"San Francisco","county":"San Francisco County","state":"California","country":"United States"},"death":{},"parents":{"father_id":"H04265","mother_id":"X02252"},"marriages":[],"tags":["california_migration","san_francisco_pioneer"],"sources":[{"short":"Edward Hooker 1909","page":"Entry 5205"}],"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"narrative_blocks":[],"cross_connections":[],"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"slug":"osgood-hooker-1897"},"X02250":{"id":"X02250","former_ids":[],"is_placeholder":false,"has_descendants_documented":true,"